14/09/2007
SOFIA, Bulgaria -- Romania, Greece and Bulgaria plan to establish a regional rapid reaction centre for national disasters, officials announced on Thursday (September 13th).
The three countries have already discussed the proposal and are now deciding where to headquarter the new centre.
Forest fires claimed 64 lives in Greece last month, while dozens of people were killed in floods in Romania and Bulgaria.
In other news Thursday, a two-day meeting of the foreign ministers of the South East European Co-operation Process opened in Sofia.
The main topic is the transformation of the Stability Pact into the Regional Co-operation Council.
(News.bg, Makfax, Fena - 13/09/07)
